    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Long Battle Over Gay Troops</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Paul Bloustein letter on July 27 editorial holds letting gays serve openly in military will not end anti-gay bias</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Pentagon's Anti-Gay Policies'' (editorial, July 27):</p>
        <p>Anti-gay bias has its origins in factors far more complex than a piece of legislation like the military's ''don't ask, don't tell'' policy adopted in 1993. To suggest that such bias will disappear if we allow gays to serve openly in the military is as wrongheaded as the policy being questioned.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Pentagon's Anti-Gay Policies'' (editorial, July 27):</p>
        <p>Anti-gay bias has its origins in factors far more complex than a piece of legislation like the military's ''don't ask, don't tell'' policy adopted in 1993. To suggest that such bias will disappear if we allow gays to serve openly in the military is as wrongheaded as the policy being questioned.</p>
        <p>Your editorial is correct in criticizing the present policy as unworkable, but a better one has yet to be defined.  PAUL BLOUSTEIN  Cincinnati, July 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
